📌 Handling Errors While Creating Cosmos DB Client

If the Cosmos DB Client fails to initialize due to:
	•	Invalid credentials (wrong endpoint or key)
	•	Network issues
	•	Timeouts
	•	Azure Cosmos DB service being down

👉 You should handle these errors at the time of client creation and ensure they don’t crash the application.

✅ Steps to Handle Errors While Creating Cosmos DB Client

1️⃣ Catch CosmosException and IllegalArgumentException while initializing the client
2️⃣ Throw a DatabaseInitializationException (custom exception)
3️⃣ Handle DatabaseInitializationException in GlobalExceptionHandler
4️⃣ Ensure a proper 500 Internal Server Error response is returned

📌 1. Update CosmosDBRepository to Handle Initialization Failures

📍 Inside CosmosDBRepository.java

import com.azure.cosmos.*;
import org.slf4j.Logger;
import org.slf4j.LoggerFactory;
import org.springframework.stereotype.Repository;

/**
 * Cosmos DB Repository for handling database connections.
 */
@Repository
public class CosmosDBRepository {

    private static final Logger logger = LoggerFactory.getLogger(CosmosDBRepository.class);
    private static CosmosClient cosmosClient;
    private static CosmosDatabase cosmosDatabase;
    private static CosmosContainer cosmosContainer;

    /**
     * Initializes Cosmos DB connection. Ensures safe handling of failures.
     *
     * @param cosmosDBConfig Configuration for DB connection.
     */
    public CosmosDBRepository(CosmosDBConfig cosmosDBConfig) {
        try {
            logger.info("🔄 Initializing Cosmos DB client...");
            cosmosClient = new CosmosClientBuilder()
                    .endpoint(cosmosDBConfig.getEndpoint())
                    .key(cosmosDBConfig.getKey())
                    .gatewayMode()
                    .consistencyLevel(ConsistencyLevel.SESSION)
                    .buildClient();

            cosmosDatabase = cosmosClient.getDatabase(cosmosDBConfig.getDatabase());
            cosmosContainer = cosmosDatabase.getContainer(cosmosDBConfig.getContainer());

            logger.info("✅ Cosmos DB connection successfully established.");

        } catch (CosmosException e) {
            logger.error("❌ Failed to initialize Cosmos DB Client! Status Code: {}, Message: {}", e.getStatusCode(), e.getMessage());
            throw new DatabaseInitializationException("Cosmos DB initialization failed. Please check DB connectivity.", e);
        } catch (IllegalArgumentException e) {
            logger.error("❌ Invalid Cosmos DB Configuration! Message: {}", e.getMessage());
            throw new DatabaseInitializationException("Invalid Cosmos DB credentials. Please check configuration.", e);
        } catch (Exception e) {
            logger.error("❌ Unexpected error during Cosmos DB initialization: ", e);
            throw new DatabaseInitializationException("Unexpected error while initializing database.", e);
        }
    }

    /**
     * Gets the Cosmos DB container.
     *
     * @return CosmosContainer instance.
     */
    public CosmosContainer getContainer() {
        return cosmosContainer;
    }
}

✅ Ensures the Cosmos DB client does not crash the application on startup.
✅ Catches initialization errors and throws DatabaseInitializationException.

📌 2. Create DatabaseInitializationException Class

📍 Inside DatabaseInitializationException.java

/**
 * Custom exception for database initialization failures.
 */
public class DatabaseInitializationException extends RuntimeException {

    /**
     * Constructs a DatabaseInitializationException with a message.
     *
     * @param message Error message.
     */
    public DatabaseInitializationException(String message) {
        super(message);
    }

    /**
     * Constructs a DatabaseInitializationException with a message and cause.
     *
     * @param message Error message.
     * @param cause The root cause of the error.
     */
    public DatabaseInitializationException(String message, Throwable cause) {
        super(message, cause);
    }
}

✅ Separates initialization errors from query execution errors.
✅ Makes it easy to catch and log initialization failures.

📌 3. Handle Initialization Failure in GlobalExceptionHandler

📍 Inside GlobalExceptionHandler.java

import org.springframework.http.HttpStatus;
import org.springframework.http.ResponseEntity;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.ExceptionHandler;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RestControllerAdvice;
import java.time.LocalDateTime;
import java.util.List;

/**
 * Global Exception Handler for API errors.
 */
@RestControllerAdvice
public class GlobalExceptionHandler {

    /**
     * Handles database initialization failures.
     */
    @ExceptionHandler(DatabaseInitializationException.class)
    public ResponseEntity<ErrorResponseDTO> handleDatabaseInitException(DatabaseInitializationException ex) {
        return ResponseEntity.status(HttpStatus.INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR)
                .body(new ErrorResponseDTO(
                        "500",
                        "Database Initialization Error",
                        List.of(new ErrorDetailDTO("CosmosDB", ex.getMessage())),
                        LocalDateTime.now()
                ));
    }
}

✅ Ensures users get a proper 500 Internal Server Error instead of a stack trace.
✅ Helps in debugging Cosmos DB connection failures easily.

